  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Key Legal Requirements:\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Customer due diligence\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\n2. Regulatory Frameworks:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- International compliance standards\n\n3. Reporting Obligations:\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Identifying potential money laundering indicators\n\n4. Potential Consequences:\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n5. Compliance Mechanisms:\n- Internal control systems\n- Staff training programs\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Independent audits\n\nFinancial institutions must proactively prevent money laundering through comprehensive compliance strategies and robust monitoring systems.",
